text: I grew up in for me one of the greatest food places which is South Louisiana where even the truck stops have great gumbo. My dad was raised in the very first place in Louisiana when the French came the first place was Nachitouches, La & he was an excellent cook, natural flair, , &  beautiful presentation. He could cook everything from any seafood (my favorite) to vegetables, bread, soups, salads, crawfish bisque, étouffée, scampi, perfect steaks, barbecue, anything you can name & to top it off the best freaking deserts & homemade old fashioned candy ever. Divinity, pralines, stuff too long to mention. My mamaw once was trying to keep busy to keep him from going out of town to have fun & I will never forget them making candy for 3 days. Then finally he said " the GD damn candy factory is closed! "  She never cursed or drank or let anyone use the Lord's  name in vain, but she laughed knowing the jig was up. He made Cafe au lait for you & drank strong chicory cafe from New Orleans.

text: I just recently watched this movie. I am not a massive fan of Bradley Cooper. But as always he portrays each character perfectly. Being a chef is very competitive. Having to be the best and create dishes that are perfect would make anyone crazy. Which Bradley captures as a man seeking redemption yet at the same time he wants the prestige.He does it the only way he knows through manipulation and his own desire which in fact was what ended his success. The relationship between Reece and Adam truly captures the respect they have for their craft which involves jealousy, competitiveness for each other but there is an unspoken respect and understanding which ultimately allow us to relate to Adam. It is at the end when Adam is having a melt down he chooses an adversary rather then a friend to see him at his weakness who understand . Love this movie and I thought I would not. Definitely on my favourite list.
